Nation Nyoka and James de Villiers, News24 Protesters in Pretoria. (News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg President Jacob Zuma says the march against immigrants in Pretoria on Friday is evidence that citizens are fed up with crime.WATCHPretoria &ndash; Police arrested 136 people in Pretoria West over the past 24 hours, including during an anti-immigrant march on Friday morning, acting police commissioner Khomotso Phahlane said.&ldquo;Although people from Mamelodi marched peacefully, a group from Atteridgeville threw stones and bricks. Confrontation with non-South Africans ensued,&rdquo; he told reporters.The violence broke out during an anti-immigration march organised by a group calling itself Mamelodi Concerned Residents.Phahlane could not say how many of those arrested were foreigners and how many South Africans.&ldquo;The situation may be exaggerated by some for their own gain. At this stage, the situation remains under control.&rdquo;The march was not solely about immigrants, but also about foreigners being involved in crime, he said.The City of Tshwane had approved the march.&ldquo;Our Constitution provides for people to express their views. Laws provide for people to apply for a march or protest." 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.